Large Language Models (LLMs) in education can accelerate both teaching and learning. AI features such as chatbots, instructional guidance, practice support, debugging assistance, and rubric/feedback generation can save time, improve performance, build confidence, and enhance learning outcomes. These tools work best when they are tailored to users' needs, interactions, and perceptions, which in turn strengthens self-efficacy. However, without thoughtful design and scaffolding, they can become counterproductive. Unrestricted AI use may lead to short-term speed and accuracy but risks undermining ''productive struggle,'' critical thinking, and long-term learning, especially in programming. A more effective approach involves participant-focused, pedagogy-aware LLMs with clear guardrails, transparent behaviors, and actionable instructor controls. This research investigates how AI tools, particularly LLM-based chatbots, can be integrated into modern block-based programming (BBP) learning platforms. The dissertation focuses on: 1.Mapping the AI feature needs of STEM and non-STEM teachers through interviews to identify shared and discipline-specific requirements. 2.Analyzing teachers' personas and perceptions of LLM chatbots through thematic analysis of professional development (PD) workshops. 3.Exploring the use of AI-generated rubrics in PD sessions, evaluating their benefits, limitations, and factors influencing adoption. 4.Examining students' attitudes toward AI-assisted assessments to design systems that are ethical, human-centered, and acceptable. 5.Investigating how students respond to LLM assistance in BBP, focusing on their emotions, perceptions, personas, and help-seeking behaviors. The findings offer evidence-based design principles for AI tools and provide a reusable measurement toolkit for evaluating their impact on performance, self-efficacy, and equity in K–12 and early undergraduate education.